Women basketball players failed to win a medal at the Under-17 World Championship, finishing fourth
The third World Cup of the seventeenth century was also won by the Americans, who defeated Spain in the final by a narrow 77:75 despite 40 points from the Spaniard Angela Salvadores.
"We really wanted to win and not be potato chips, but maybe we wanted it too much. We caught the beginning, but we didn't manage to keep it, because they rolled us under the basket," regretted captain Karolína Malečková. "But playing in front of such an audience was an incredible experience," she praised the fans in Klatovy and Pilsen.
The Czechs started very well, taking an 8-0 lead thanks to two three-pointers and dominating the field throughout the first quarter. At that moment, it seemed that they would repay their opponents for the 85-88 defeat from the basic group after extra time. However, the referees whistled 15 fouls at half-time and helped Hungary return to the game with a 12-2 streak.
"I am convinced that it would have been enough to score another two or three baskets, run to 20 points and we would not have let it go. But instead, our mistakes came. I am not interested in the referees, but in what we did wrong, and there were mistakes that helped the opponent to catch up," said coach Richard Fousek.
"It wasn't the first time we had a lapse in concentration. But the girls are fighters, they didn't let anything go and fought to the end. But the opponent was very good," he added.
The Czechs were kept in the game mainly by Petr Holešínská's accurate shooting from distance and the pivot Tereza Šípová. However, the best Czech shooter had a problem with fouls and missed a large part of the third quarter on the court. The Hungarians took advantage of this and gained a slight lead, which they kept, even though the Czechs fought until the last seconds.
"For us, the first five games were very demanding, we rotated the games in a tight rotation and it cost us a lot of effort. Already against Spain, it was clear that the girls were tired and there was nowhere to take them. Because of the physicality, we were not consistent in defense. We did not play a quick counterattack, we lacked a rebound. And the Hungarians are so good that if you do not put everything together, it is difficult to win," added Fousek.
He believes that his charges have a promising future ahead of them. "In two years, the girls have managed to win the Youth Olympics, come second at the European Championship for 16-year-olds and are now fourth in the world. By our standards, they are a quality team with a good character and it is necessary to continue working with them and developing their talent. Now it is up to the federation to decide which coach they will assign to them in the higher categories," added Fousek.
Thomas Cook: Czechs thrown out of hotel in Mallorca. Guarantees were not enough
The Austrian, German and Polish divisions of the group also filed for insolvency during the week. The future of the Czech branch is currently being discussed and a decision should be made by the end of September.
According to the vice-chairman of the Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, Jan Papež, there are three possible solutions in play - liquidation will be announced, or the company will be sold, or a team from the Czech branch will establish a new travel agency. "Which one it will be, however, cannot be predicted, it will depend on the German owner," he told the Czech News Agency today.
In addition to the two prematurely terminated trips, the travel agency is also dealing with cases where clients had to pay for their stay on their own, although the company is trying to provide guarantees to hoteliers. The travel agency has promised to reimburse its clients, according to the Pope, the company has sufficient security for this.
The problems in the hotels arose primarily in Mallorca, where the company also asked the Czech consulate for help. In this context, the Pope described to ČTK one of the cases where the local hotel threw out all the tourists of the office. "The hotelier could not determine who belongs to the German company and who belongs to the Czech company. Therefore, he threw everyone out of the hotel, even though the domestic Neckermann provided a guarantee," he said. According to Šrámek, the situation was eventually resolved.
The Czech branch of the bankrupt British group Thomas Cook increased its sales to 995 million crowns last year, an increase of almost 21 percent year-on-year, according to the company's annual report. It covers the accounting period from October 2017 to the end of September 2018. The company's net profit, on the other hand, decreased by about seven million to 15.3 million crowns. However, the company had an unpaid loss of almost 103 million crowns from previous years. The branch includes two basic divisions - in addition to CK Neckermann, it is also the company Global Travel Lufthansa City Center.
