Nokia is suing a Brno company over the name Lokia. People will not confuse us, Moravians believe
Nokia has filed an objection to the application of the Lokia brand to the Industrial Property Office. However, according to the CCV, product substitution is not likely.
The Brno-based company developing the CCV software is facing legal action from the Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. The Finns do not like the fact that the Brno-based company's warehouse management program is called Lokia WMS, wrote the E15 daily. Nokia has therefore filed an objection against the application of the Lokia brand to the Industrial Property Office. CCV believes that confusion is not likely.
Marketing Director Petr Ondrášek said that the program is already being used by two dozen customers and has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand is recognized and trusted around the world, and when someone attempts to register a mark that we believe is likely to cause confusion or dilute our brand, we take action to protect our valuable asset," Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant said.
The Brno developers claim that they did not think about the brand, famous in the past for its mobile phones, when creating the warehouse program. According to the CCV, the name Lokia is based on the Latin name for a type of dragonfly, whose rapid movement is supposed to be an analogy of the movement of warehouse workers around the warehouse.
"On the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software that companies use to equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really heading into the field of mobile phone production. And we do not want to be compared to a brand that may be missing the train in its field," CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák responded in E15.
CCV applied for trademark protection at the Industrial Property Office in August, before the program was launched on the market. "It applied for protection for products and services belonging to classes 9, 35 and 42, since the software belongs to class 9, the related business management services in the warehouse belong to class 35 and the development of computer software to class 42 according to the international classification," said Ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that the earlier Nokia trademark is valid in all classes of goods and services, and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services, and therefore, of course, also overlaps in classes 9, 35 and 42. "CCV does not dispute the opponent's assertion as far as the conformity of these classes of goods and services is concerned. In reality, however, they are completely different brands aimed at different target groups," said Ondrášek.
According to E15, the dispute over the brand may last for months and it may complicate the company's activities.
