Epilepsy complicated his love for sports, but thanks to the operation he has new hope
Honzík's parents first noticed that something was wrong with him when he was a year and a half old. He always stared into space for a few minutes, became immobile and did not respond to anyone. The paediatrician therefore sent him to a children's neurological clinic, where, after a series of examinations, the doctors diagnosed him with epilepsy and immediately put him on medication, which did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for the doctors to find the ideal combination of drugs, thanks to which he completely stopped having seizures. At the age of five, the doctors stopped the medication, and because the seizures did not return, the parents thought that Honza was healthy and began to encourage him to do more sports. He rode a bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, and spent his free time playing games with his sister and friends. At the age of eleven, however, he had another seizure and everything started again.
Doctors again tried various combinations of drugs, but this time nothing worked, seizures in the form of absences were constantly repeated. Since Honza always lost consciousness during a seizure, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get injured. Gradually, Honza stopped riding a bike and exchanged downhill skis for cross-country skis and a snowboard. Although the sport caused him a seizure from time to time, he never gave it up completely. He even fulfilled his dream and ran the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who kept an eye on him to help in case of emergency.
When Honza was 15 years old, his parents decided to try to change doctors and turned to specialists at the University Hospital in Motol. After a series of examinations, the doctors there decided that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove a lesion from his brain - the source of epileptic seizures. "I had to undergo two operations in a row. First, the doctors implanted probes into my brain that monitored its activity, and only then were they able to remove the lesion. It was hell for me for several weeks. I just had to lie there and hardly move, with wires sticking out of my head that were connected to a computer," recalls Honza.
The operation was successful and the doctors removed the relatively large lesion. "The first days after the operation were very mentally demanding, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and hardly spoke. Compared to how lively and communicative he normally is, it was a frightening change, but fortunately everything returned to normal after a few days," describes his mother and adds: "A month and a half after the operation he had 1 seizure, but according to the doctors it happens. Since then he has been seizure-free for 3 months."
In this school year, Honza will graduate. In addition to sports, he enjoys languages and has begun to cooperate with the E Society, with which he goes to schools for discussions about epilepsy. Honza is not yet fully engaged in sports activities, he is starting to return to sports gradually. "I am learning how to play sports properly, how to breathe well so that I do not expose my body to sudden stress, which is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, therefore, he will not yet actively participate in the traditional EPPI boating triathlon, which brings together patients with epilepsy and healthy athletes and which takes place this weekend on 28 September 2019 at the Veselská sand pit. But maybe next year.
