The incident was reported at around 08:00 at the 22nd kilometre in the direction of Prague. "The motorway is closed, at least for freight traffic. Passenger cars can drive through the petrol station," said police spokeswoman Michaela Richterová in the morning. Traffic was restored at around 14:30. According to Richterová, the preliminary damage is at least two million crowns, and the cause of the accident is being investigated by police.
A spokesman for the Central Bohemian fire brigade, Petr Svoboda, said that one truck was transporting passenger vehicles and the other plastic granulate. "Due to the large impact, the transported vehicles were displaced, which the fire brigade had to first secure against a possible fall," he added.
One of the cars had a damaged fuel tank, from which about 200 liters of diesel leaked. The firefighters managed to pump out another 200 liters. Employees of the environmental department of the Beroun town hall were called to the accident because of the fuel leak. The recovery of the crashed vehicles and the opening of the highway was ensured by a private company, which also extracted the contaminated soil.
Microplastics have reached the human gut, study confirms for the first time
A team led by Professor Philipp Schwabl of the University of Vienna has published a study that for the first time proves the presence of microplastics in human faeces. The study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - however, tiny plastic particles measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in the samples of all examined persons. None of the eight subjects was a vegetarian, six of them did not avoid sea fish, all of them drank water from plastic bottles and food packaged in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the needs of the cosmetics industry, or are formed by the disintegration of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and soft drinks; in short, everywhere on the planet. Their entry into the human digestive tract has therefore only been officially confirmed. There were about 20 particles of microplastics per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them.
However, mankind still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on the "host" organisms. Small particles can get into the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. "This is the first study of its kind and has confirmed what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of the occurrence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system, thereby facilitating the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will be to at least stop its steep increase. As far as plastic bottles are concerned, experts estimate that in three years humanity will consume a fifth more than today. The current rate is a staggering one million bottles bought per minute. Every year, about eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and contaminates the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already introduced restrictions and other measures, Kenya, for example, has banned plastic bags - under the threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering small bans (the well-known straws), and the Czech Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. Critics, however, argue that such measures are nice, but completely insufficient.
The repair of the Krkonoše Museum will be delayed by a year
The administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) has postponed the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original deadline for opening the envelopes was September 20, said Radek Drahný, spokesman for the national park. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submitting bids is the reduction of the budget from 110 million crowns to 83 million crowns.
"We are currently working with the prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, it is the price that we expect to be offered. If someone makes an offer that is acceptable, the work will begin as soon as possible," said Drahný.
Compared to the original plans, the start of the repair of the museum is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have a selected contractor for the construction part by the end of last year and to start construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park administration, the European subsidies of 123 million crowns for the project are not at risk.
The KRNAP administration has not been able to select a construction company for the repairs of the museum. It announced a second tender this summer, because in the previous tender all the offers of companies significantly exceeded the then expected price of 65 million. The offers exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is located in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since the autumn of 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total costs, including the construction of a new exhibition, are estimated at 210 million crowns. The KRNAP visitor centre should be built in the now vacated building by the end of 2021 after the transformation of the exhibitions.
The renovated museum with a new interactive exhibition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful Stone and Life exhibition, should serve as a representative gateway to the Giant Mountains for visitors. The visitor centre should provide information about the past and present of the Giant Mountains in the most understandable form and motivate people to discover the mountains and protect them. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The centre will also offer opportunities to organise concerts, festivals, theatre performances or lectures in the open air. The plans include the construction of a new entrance to the building, the creation of a research room and a café.
On Saturday, Česká spořitelna erroneously charged some card payments twice.
It has already corrected the error
Česká spořitelna erroneously charged its clients twice for some card payments on Saturday afternoon.
According to the bank's spokesman, Lukas Kropik, the problem could have affected thousands of transactions.
The savings bank has already rectified the error and returned the money to the clients.
The savings bank noticed problems with the double charging of card payments on Saturday afternoon.
"Yesterday (Saturday) night, we updated the system and all these duplicate payments were immediately returned to the clients.
At the moment everything is working without any problems," said Kropík on Sunday afternoon.
A spokesman for the bank does not know the exact number of clients to whom the bank deducted money from card payments twice; according to his estimate, there were fewer than a thousand transactions.
The savings bank is investigating the causes of the problems.
"It could have been a combination of several factors," Kropík said.
Česká spořitelna is the largest bank in the Czech Republic in terms of the number of clients.
At the end of March, it had 4.6 million.
The owner of the savings bank is the Austrian financial group Erste Group Bank, which is a key player in the banking market of Central and Eastern Europe.
