"A frightening result of the study." Islam does not belong in the West, the vast majority of Austrians think
1,200 respondents were questioned, and the survey shows a considerable distrust of Islam in Austrian society.
Almost 60 percent of Austrians fear that some Muslims are terrorists, and 48 percent would call for a ban on the construction of mosques. 80 percent of respondents are in favour of greater surveillance of Islamic centres.
A majority of Austrians also want Muslims to be restricted in their religious practices and say they sometimes feel like foreigners in their own country because of the presence of Muslims.
"The result of the study is frightening," says the author of the study, Wolfgang Aschauer, adding: "Such a tendency towards ethnocentrism could eventually lead to the adoption of discriminatory attitudes. There is a risk that the religious freedoms granted to Muslims will be narrowed."
Among believers, the critical attitude is less pronounced. Aschauer argues that in Austria it is not a conflict between religions, but between cultures. According to the sociologist, dialogue and education could help blunt polarization.
According to the study, the most hostile attitudes towards Muslims are held by extreme right-wing voters, people without a university degree and senior citizens over the age of 75. On the other hand, Green voters, people under the age of 30 and university students are the most welcoming.
According to estimates by the Austrian Ministry of the Interior, about 700,000 Muslims live in Austria, which has a population of about 8.7 million. The vast majority have Turkish roots. There are more than 400 Muslim places of worship and mosques in the country, and Islam has been officially recognized as a religion here since 1912.
Which cities will disappear under the sea?
The vote of the upper house of the Canadian Parliament confirmed a well-known rumor for several days: Canada is revoking the honorary citizenship of the former legend of the struggle for human rights, Nobel Peace Prize winner Daw Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest for trying to bring freedom to her country, lost her honorary title because of her participation in the genocide against the minority Rohingya people.
The decision to strip Suu Kyi of her honorary citizenship was approved by the lower legislative body a week ago, and senators have now unanimously supported it. "This is the right message for her, for Myanmar and for the whole world," independent senator Ratna Omidvar commented on the decision of her colleagues. "We must make it clear that accomplices to genocide are not welcome here in Canada - especially as honorary citizens."
The verdict of the Canadian parliament does not technically change anything for Suu Kyi, it is only an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it is a strong message for her. The silence of the long-time human rights campaigner on the atrocities that the army of Buddhist-majority Myanmar has been committing for endless months against the Rohingya Muslim minority is unbearable.
The fact that an officially organized genocide is taking place in Myanmar and that Suu Kyi - the de facto prime minister of the government there - has completely failed in her duty to protect her citizens was recently brought to light by a UN report. Specifically, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigation team, should stand trial for crimes against humanity committed in actions that - as the report says - "shock both by the horror of their actions and by their enormous scale." Suu Kyi and her administration, according to the UN, committed complicity primarily by covering up the actions of the soldiers and releasing a protective fog of lies around them - for example, that it was an "anti-terrorist operation."
After the removal of Suu Kyi, five personalities remain on the list of honorary citizens of Canada: the Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tenzin Gyatso, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th Imam of Shia Muslims and Malala Yousafzai.
The development around the former icon of the struggle for freedom and democracy was also reflected by the Canadian Museum for Human Rights, where information about the atrocities against the Rohingya and the parliamentary decision to strip her of the title of honorary citizen were added to Suu Kyi's profile. "We have also dimmed the lighting of her photo on the board depicting the timeline of the struggle for human rights and we are thinking about replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Canadian media quoted museum spokesman Rory McLeod as saying.
The only thing that will remain in Suu Kyi's current turmoil - at least for the time being - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her at the suggestion of Václav Havel in 1991 for her enormous contribution to the struggle for democracy. "Even though Ms Suu Kyi's current actions are regrettable, her award will not be annulled," the head of the Nobel Foundation, Lars Heikensten, told the Canadian CBS.
