Tech companies want to rule our cities
In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, the political scientist Francis Fukuyama wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man: "What we may be witnessing ... is the end point of mankind's ideological evolution and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of government."
Twenty-six years later, from the United States to Russia, from Turkey to Poland and from Hungary to Italy, we are witnessing the triumph of illiberal models and the rise of various forms of nationalism and radicalism. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to come to terms with the emergence of these forces. As his interview with George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he is rethinking many of his former positions: he claims that the ideas of socialism should return to the public space and that Marx was right in many respects. At the same time, he insists that his intellectual development is still in line with the position of the 1990s and that the critics of The End of History and the Last Man have not understood correctly.
"What I was saying back then was that one of the problems with modern democracy is that it provides peace and prosperity, but people want more than that... Liberal democracy doesn't even try to define what a good life is. It leaves it up to individuals who feel alienated, don't see the point, and therefore group themselves into identity groups that give them a sense of belonging."
At the time, The End of History and the Last Man was written as a powerful argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When Fukuyama is asked how he now perceives the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, he replies: "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we are talking about ownership of the means of production, then I don't think it will work, except when clear public services are in demand. But if you mean redistributive programs that try to solve the huge imbalances in income and wealth that we are witnessing, then yes. I think not only could it come back, it should come back. The long period that President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher started, in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of an unregulated market came into play, had a disastrous effect in many ways."
Finally, Fukuyama tries to calm down the current situation and warns all liberals that even the emergence of new regimes that are not entirely democratic will not mean the end of history.
Civilization on Borrowed Time
Recently, I remembered a beautiful "order" from one of the great stories by Šimek and Grossmann, set partly in a cemetery, which reads as follows: "I warned her that she was crying well, but on someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many world politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving in a very similar way.
They behave as if humans ruled the planet Earth. In reality, we are just a speck on its surface, which it can blow out with its enormous forces like a candle flame. Probably few of them watch the famous British and American natural science documentaries dealing with the destructive capabilities of our blue marble. After all, it would be enough for one of the larger active volcanoes to "blow up" and our advanced civilization would be ruined.
And it is highly likely that this will happen in the near future. According to leading volcanologists, a number of large volcanoes are "locked and loaded" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it has to happen, happened as soon as possible, before trillions of dollars are wasted on measures aimed at reducing the production of carbon dioxide, because any really angry volcano can release it, along with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, into the atmosphere at least a hundred times more than was saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
Forcibly limiting the production of CO2 therefore makes no sense. In addition, it has been scientifically proven that with a significantly higher proportion of CO2 in the air, plants produce more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For humanity, a possible warming is significantly more favourable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
If we realize the still insufficiently studied influence of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we must come to only one reasonable conclusion: Let's try hard to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let's try to adapt to other changes, with which we cannot compete, with the least possible cost!
The Water Sprite and Caroline
When the water sprite Jonáš and the miller's daughter Karolínka fall in love with each other, it is not easy at all.
Jonas is prevented from falling in love by his father, the grumpy water sprite Hastrbuch, while Caroline has no idea that her beloved Jonas is not human.
Fortunately, there is a young man, Libor, who will do everything in his power to protect the whole village, and especially Karolína, from the villain of Vodnice.
What does it matter if he schemes and lies?
Especially if he can get Karolína to reject Jonáš in favour of him, the valiant Libor.
Soon it becomes clear to everyone in the village who is to blame for the drowning of the night watchman Konvička, the spoiled flour, the fire in the mill and other villainy.
The angry villagers organize a hunt for the water sprite, and on top of that an implacable water sprite curse falls on Jonah's head.
And now, Konvička's little soul, advise Karolína!
