Only children. We do not have a certain reproduction, but we do not have to scare
Some words have ominous connotations, even though they only convey a state of affairs. One of them is the word "one-child." It refers to a child growing up without siblings, but it does not sound neutral. "You know, an only child," is said without the need to add anything. It is interesting that "one-child" has had this feature for a long time, even from the times when expressions such as the demographic crisis were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is necessary to ensure the simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no state in Europe today reaches this value. At most, France or Sweden are close to it, but the simple reproduction rate of the population is not ensured by European states. (In the West, only Israel stands out with a total fertility of 3.1 children per woman.) It is a situation made for alarmism. Therefore, it is not surprising that the Minister of Labor and Social Affairs Maláčová also falls for it: "There are almost as many one-child families as two-child families," she said in an interview with LN. But she forgot the devil hidden in the detail.
Yes, it is good to draw attention to the problem, instead of downplaying or ideologizing it, as in Germany, where the campaign for more children easily gets the label of fascism (in the style of "even Hitler supported it"). It is good to be reminded that many couples directly plan to have only children. It is good if politicians show the will to remove the obstacles that lead to these decisions (for example, the weak spread of work from home discourages women from further pregnancies). But despite all this, let us point out one thing.
When Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost as many single children," there is a drop of demagogy in it. That statement was appropriate twenty years ago. Let us recall that fertility in the Czech Republic last ensured simple reproduction in 1980 ("Husák's children"). Then it fell to a terrible 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost fifty percent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is above the European average. It is still not enough for simple reproduction, so the activity of politicians is appropriate. Only with this alarmism can they reduce a little.
