Declaration of the end of the right in the Chamber of Deputies, or what kind of "right-wing" coalition of ODS, TOP 09, STAN and KDU?
Recently, there have been reports in the media and in commentaries about an upcoming coalition of the aforementioned parties. Many are applauding the fact that the "right" is finally coming together, but I rather wonder why these parties are still calling themselves right-wing.
If I ignore the new Trikolora movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it does not matter at all how the subjects label themselves or what label is parroted by the mainstream media. ODS is hardly centrist in its average of top politicians of this party, TOP 09 is clearly a party of the urban pseudo-liberal left (which is ashamed of its leftism and thus hypocritically describes itself as conservative or even right-wing). STAN is a party that basically merges with TOP 09 in its concept, ideology and voter targeting (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And KDU even labels itself as centrist for a long time - but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
If I consider myself a classically liberal right-wing voter, the highest value for me is the freedom of the individual, the free market and minimal state interference in the lives of individuals and the economy. How do these parties fulfil this general assumption of right-wingness? How many laws cutting people's freedoms by the salami method, increasing taxes, confirming new regulations and increasing surveillance, increasing ties to the socialist EU or supporting environmental and gender madness have they supported in recent years? A lot, really a lot. Not their own labels, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all kinds of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And that has nothing to do with right-wingness.
I would not be at all surprised by the coalition cooperation of TOP 09, STAN and KDU, they simply belong together on the political map and, except for Christian or, on the contrary, homosexual and gender aspects, I basically do not see any obvious difference in them for voters in terms of the influence of the state on their lives. However, ODS has long portrayed itself as "the only right-wing party" and, by associating with these three entities, it no longer openly reveals its true political classification.
By the way, when I briefly mentioned the labels, have you noticed how often all these parties quite consistently and cheaply label the critics of dirigisme and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Are they unable or just unwilling to understand that there are many people for whom Euro-socialism and the growing lack of freedom do not smell as strongly as the authoritarian regime in Russia? Are they not concealing their complete inability to argue and their groundless or blind adoration of Euro-EU conditions?
In short, it is possible that in the Czech Republic, politics other than the center no longer has a chance of greater success. Maybe voters really want such a combination. Maybe they want left-of-center politics under the guise of the "right," because they are ashamed of their political beliefs (or they can't even identify them). I don't know. But I am definitely not one of those voters.
