Czechs in Europe by Ondřej Houska: Should Czechoslovakia have rejected the Munich Agreement in 1938 and gone to war with Germany? Three times NO
An undated photo shows Adolf Hitler during a visit to the Czechoslovak border fortifications. The purpose of the fortifications was never to stop the German army, but to slow down its advance until the Allies got involved.
If, almost exactly 81 years ago, Czechoslovakia had rejected the Munich Agreement and subsequently faced a German attack, what would have knocked the most Czechoslovak soldiers out of the fight? German tanks, air force, or perhaps artillery? Quite possibly it would not have been any of these weapons, even though the Germans had an overwhelming advantage over the Czechoslovaks in them. The Czechoslovak army would probably have suffered the greatest losses - due to blisters.
Charges dropped in Nantes cathedral fire, man confesses
The Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul in the heart of Nantes caught fire last Saturday, severely damaging the original 16th century stained glass windows and destroying the organ.
Investigators investigated the suspicion of arson due to the fact that the fire advanced through the temple from three different places.
At the same time, the police found no signs at the entrances that anyone had forced their way into the cathedral.
The accused is a volunteer with the local diocese, a 39-year-old Rwandan refugee.
Police arrested him shortly after the fire, but then released him without pursuing criminal charges.
Now the prosecutor's office has reported that, on the basis of new evidence, the man was arrested again on Saturday, confessed and is facing charges of arson.
If found guilty, he faces up to ten years in prison and a hefty fine.
According to his lawyer, the man regrets the act and has decided to fully cooperate with the investigators, Le Monde wrote.
Zeman the preservationist - The man stretching the constitution calls for the enforcement of the law
Those who move in a society divided into camps and do not want to go completely mad will welcome situations where they do not have to cheer only for their own. When they can admit the pluses to those whom they otherwise criticize. If only so that they do not have the feeling that they are orienting themselves only according to pre-assigned labels. Such situations include the list of heavily damaged monuments that President Zeman fences with during his favorite trips to the regions.
Everyone knows what is going on. And anyone who occasionally travels through the Czech Republic sees many of the devastated monuments - from the centres of historic towns to individual castles, monasteries, old houses, churches or farms - with their own eyes. Everyone suspects that demagogy may also come into play here. That if we accuse the town hall of not caring about monuments or some horror in the zoning plan, it may be the work of former administrations. Or a privatised object whose owner is not traceable. The head of state calls on local politicians: "The section of the Heritage Act allows you to fine the owners of objects who do not take care of their property." But even if the owner is untraceable, it must be admitted that the president calls for the enforcement of the law. Which even critics of his bending of the constitution should recognise as a plus.
Of course, Miloš Zeman would not be Miloš Zeman if he considered all the details and formalities of a complex problem. But he stands up for a good cause, just like the squatters, whom he himself does not recognize. Two years ago, we wrote: "Despite all the abuse, the squatters draw attention to a problem that is beyond the current interest. To the fact that this or that building is in a state of disrepair." And let's admit that the president is de facto doing the same thing.
If you come to the historic center of Jáchymov, you will be amazed at how devastated it is - including the houses with Renaissance cores. At a time when Jáchymov is celebrating 500 years of silver mining and the minting of thalers (for Americans, dollars). Why? Apparently because of the quick sale of houses in the 1990s, local officials say. But why is it that seven kilometers away, Ostrov, the seat of the Šliks, who minted the Jáchymov thalers, has a nicely repaired historical core? It is good if the president draws attention to these things.
Vojtěch: On Monday we will present a "traffic light" for epidemiological measures
The new system is intended to fulfil the role of a pandemic plan, the absence of which has led to criticism of the government and the Ministry of Health.
"The levels will be according to the strength of community spread," the minister explained.
He added that at present, for example, the Moravian-Silesian Region or Prague would reach the middle, orange level.
The system is designed as a regional one, because the situation in individual regions varies significantly, he added.
The ministry worked with epidemiologists and the Institute of Health Information and Statistics (IHIS) on the system.
According to the minister, specific measures will be linked to the individual levels, whether it is the obligation to wear masks or the organization of special departments in hospitals.
Interior Minister Jan Hamáček (ČSSD) called for the creation of an epidemiological plan in the Prima Partie television programme, according to which people should have clear information about what measures they can expect if the epidemiological situation worsens.
The daily increase in confirmed cases in the Czech Republic has been growing in recent days, although the number of people hospitalized remains low.
Vojtěch commented that nothing major was happening and that it was not appropriate to talk about declaring a state of emergency or reconvening the crisis management team.
In view of the growing number of infected people, the government has reintroduced the obligation to wear masks at indoor events of more than 100 people throughout the Czech Republic from Saturday.
From Monday, the capacity of these events will be limited to 500 people, now it is 1000 people.
The government's approach, where it was not clear until the last minute what measures and when they would come into force or when they would be announced, was criticised.
"I think that in a situation that is quite tense, the main actors should, on the contrary, create a sense of security and, on the contrary, straighten out the confusion," Senator Marek Hilšer said in Questions.
The measures can already vary according to the region, for example, in Prague from Sunday it is mandatory to wear masks even in non-residential medical facilities, for example in pharmacies or in doctor's waiting rooms.
The obligation to wear masks when visiting health and social care facilities or pharmacies has also been introduced in the Liberec and Ústí regions since Friday.
In the Vysočina region in the Jihlava region, it has been necessary to wear masks in indoor public spaces, on public transport and in healthcare facilities since 14 July.
On the other hand, anti-epidemic measures have been relaxed in the Moravian-Silesian Region, as well as in the Central Bohemian Region in the Kutná Hora region.
At the beginning of June, the Czech government also approved the so-called traffic light for Europe, which distinguishes the level of risk of infection in individual European countries and accordingly adjusts the rules applicable to entry into the Czech Republic from these countries.
For countries with a low and medium risk, the authorities have not required Czech citizens to test negative for the coronavirus since 15 June or have not ordered quarantine instead.
These are mandatory for the return of Czechs from high-risk countries.
At the moment, all EU member states are now in the low risk category.
Costa Rica is a champion in the fight against climate change
Costa Rica received the title for several reasons. For starters, for the plan to be carbon neutral by 2050 - however, many countries have committed to this under the Paris Agreement. The Central American state with a population of about five million produces only 0.4 percent of global emissions. Costa Rica has also committed to fully switch to renewable energy sources by 2030, with 70 percent of buses or taxis running on electricity.
The official tourism organization reports that about 95 percent of the energy already comes from renewable sources - in 2017, Costa Rica ran on them for a total of 300 days.
Costa Rica boasts almost thirty national parks.
Rainforests with diverse fauna and flora, which cover more than half of the country's territory, are also one of the main tourist attractions. "Costa Rica is a pioneer in the field of nature conservation and sets an example for other countries in the region and around the world. Climate change requires urgent action from all of us," the UN said in a statement.
Costa Rica can boast of almost thirty national parks, which is really a lot considering the small size of the country (51,100 square kilometers). Rain or cloud forests, coral reefs or mangrove swamps are home to five percent of the world's biodiversity. The country also has volcanoes, picturesque waterfalls and you can also find several rescue stations for sloths.
