Thank you for the dance! Leonard Cohen's final album to be released posthumously
Thanks for the Dance will feature unreleased material and various musical collaborations put together by the singer's son, and will be released on 22 November.
In October 2016, the album You Want it Darker was released, on which Cohen collaborated with his son Adam. He asked him to help him finish the individual songs. On the intimate recording, Cohen symbolically comes to terms with his impending death. He died a month after the release of the album at the age of 82.
Seven months later, Adam Cohen began to work on the material left to him by his father. He invited a number of musicians to work with him - Damien Rice, Bryce Dessner, Javier Mas and the singer Beck.
"When we came up with the music for my father's words, we used his own characteristic musical techniques. So he is still with us," said Adam Cohen about the album. "What impresses me most about it are the reactions of those who have already heard it. One after the other, they say that Leonard is still alive," he added.
The first swallow of the album is the short song The Goal. "I'm almost alive, I'm almost home," Cohen sings in his characteristic honeyed voice. He sang about death, he suspected that he would not live to see the release of new material. He even admitted it in an interview with The New Yorker magazine a month before his death. "I'm ready to die. I hope it won't be too unpleasant," he said.
In September 2018, Adam Cohen published a collection of his father's poetry called The Flame, which will be published by Argo on 31 December.
Going on holiday with just a credit card? The NEO account offers free withdrawals from ATMs all over the world!
According to surveys, about half of all Czechs who travel abroad have already got used to paying directly by card. The main reasons include convenience, security, but also the possibility of using travel insurance, which is often associated with a payment card.
The convenience of paying by card can be appreciated by travellers in almost every corner of the world. This is especially true in popular tourist destinations, but nowadays payment cards are accepted almost everywhere. "People who travel more often, for example for work, do not have time to repeatedly go to exchange offices to exchange cash. And even "holidaymakers" do not want to rely on the fact that cash is enough for them. In addition, Czech banks or exchange offices do not even have some foreign currencies. For the NEO account, we have therefore solved this so that its users can withdraw cash from all ATMs free of charge, wherever they are," says Kateřina Petko, Director of Marketing and Communications and Spokesperson of Expobank CZ.
In addition, a payment card is a much more reliable way of not losing your money than cash. If you lose a full wallet, its owner may not be able to wait for the money he carried in it. However, if he only loses his payment card, he can easily block it immediately over the phone or via online banking. If he acts quickly, he may not suffer any financial loss at all. "In addition to their reliable protection, keeping money in a bank account has other advantages. For example, the NEO account has an interest rate of 1.6% per year, which is one of the highest among current and savings accounts. Its establishment and management takes place completely online without the need to visit a branch. In addition, the money in the bank account is insured up to 100 thousand euros and account management is completely free," adds Kateřina Petko.
For anyone who is going to travel abroad, travel insurance should be a matter of course. Thanks to the possibility of arranging it and paying by card online, it can be done even at the last minute. However, the mere possession of a payment card often means insurance protection when traveling. "For example, with embossed MasterCard Gold and MasterCard Business cards, travel insurance is an integral part of foreign travel to all countries of the world. Holders of these cards can also insure their family with whom they are traveling. They often do not need any further arrangements," adds Kateřina Petko from Expobank CZ. However, it is always advisable to check the scope of the insurance, i.e. whether it covers all activities that travelers plan to undertake.
