Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and does not know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to determine whether it can hold cryptocurrencies, responding to a request from state-run Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which wants to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then have the bank pay the oil company's suppliers in cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now near a 30-year low, Bloomberg reported, citing four sources.
Sanctions imposed by the United States on the authoritarian regime of President Nicolás Maduro have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system, deepening the country's economic crisis - one of the most severe in the world - and forcing officials to use a patchwork of different ways to move money. While Maduro's efforts to launch the world's first state cryptocurrency have failed, continued efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Venezuela's central bank and PDVSA did not respond to requests for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ethers, or how much value it holds in those currencies. The company has had trouble getting payments from customers through conventional channels because major banks are unwilling to do business with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of a $700 million payment in Chinese yuan because the parties were unable to find financial institutions that would facilitate the transaction.
PDVSA may not want to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to register on the stock exchange and undergo due diligence. Instead, it wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank to pay the entities to which PDVSA owes money. The oil company's representatives believe that the central bank is less exposed to any obstacles that may arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized online ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions, in some cases allowing for relatively anonymous transfers without the need for a middleman. Few banks are involved in digital currencies because of the money laundering and customer information issues that come with them and complicate compliance.
After the debacle of 2018, cryptocurrencies are experiencing a return to the limelight this year thanks to expectations of their greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen by almost 20 percent in the last four days, but it has gained about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
Commentary by Jan Šindelář: Managing the railways as a company
The heavenly election, although it may not have been completely smooth, is the culmination of a sad story about the inability of the state to give a clear direction to the railways. The board has been incomplete for over a year and even after Wednesday evening this does not change because one of the members resigned. The provisional period continues.
The selection process itself was a farce from the beginning, if only because the requirements for candidates, especially in the field of practice, were significantly relaxed. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate was to work in the past were reduced. First, the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board only played the role of pimps.
Nebeský submitted probably the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company, he beat experienced players from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. It was the participation of interesting managers from the private sector that was probably the brightest side (and the greatest hope) of the whole process. Today, those concerned know that they only played the role of narrative backdrops in a political game.
Perhaps Nebeský will surprise, show great talent and ultimately prove to be the best railway boss of all time. At least in the beginning, however, he will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political smoke and mirrors. Czech Railways does not expect an easy period, they have to cope with competition in the liberalization of the market and with a shortage of employees in operation. Train drivers, shunters and mechanics are missing. What motivation should they have for further work and respect for management, when the state behaves in top management like an elephant in a china shop?
The second important group is the creditors. We will see how they interpret the games at the head of the railways next spring, when the railways will defend the rating. It is certain that the creditors perceive the instability. The sad thing is that someone else goes to Moody's every year to defend the rating for Czech Railways. The agency has not missed the frequent changes in the management of the railways and the political influence on the company, it has already criticized them this summer.
The ANO movement promotes, among other things, the slogan that the state should be managed as a company. For a start, it would be enough if one large state-owned company was managed as a company and not as a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if they were led by the best. They applied, but the state scorned them. It can certainly be argued that the post at the head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive the antics with the selection process.
An unusually open and unique image of Karel Gott in the feature documentary film by Olga Špátová
This unique film project by Olga Špátová will premiere in Czech cinemas in the spring of next year.
"In the middle of September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would make a documentary about his life with Karel again after ten years. I did not hesitate for a minute! It was and is a great honour for me to film with a person who has remained in the limelight of Czech culture for more than half a century thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable hard work. I accepted the challenge to make a feature-length documentary film about Karel Gott, who has been bringing joy to three generations of listeners with his art, as a commitment to this legendary singer," director Olga Špátová describes her feelings.
Thanks to a quick arrangement and agreement, the first day of shooting took place on October 22 last year and the last shots with Karel Gott were shot a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to authentically capture Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who gives himself to his fans, as a painter, but at the same time a loving husband and father of his children. A man who has been giving joy to several generations with his songs for sixty years, not only in our country, but also in Europe, and in fact all over the world. A man who has written himself into the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not intended to be a showcase of the indisputable fame of Karel Gott and his achievements. "That's why it's not even possible to compare my previous film, The Gott Phenomenon, with this current one. Everyone is different. At least because we filmed them in a different stage of Karel Gott's life, and this is very evident in his personal, almost intimate confession, which he gave us and which confirmed for all of us what a legend we have the opportunity to work with and spend time with, which is truly indescribable," adds Olga Špátová.
The filmmakers captured Karel Gott during his performances, during meetings with his fans here and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, at the cottage in Bohemian Switzerland, in the village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thanks to Karel Gott's sincere openness, the film will be completely authentic and unique.
"Olga has the great gift of filming with her close team in such a way that we often let ourselves be carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, thanks to which I talked about relatively confidential topics. With her husband, cameraman Jan Malíř, they actually became part of our family. Originally, we wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life anniversary. But because I still had a beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot for as long as possible. Well, and because there were a lot of me everywhere in 2019, my wish was that it would be released in cinemas in the spring of next year. This documentary film is a thank you to my supporters and all those who supported and accompanied me in my profession," says Karel Gott himself about the film.
