The library commemorates the anniversary of the death of Wenceslas IV with an exhibition of manuscripts
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, i.e. from the time of the Roman and Czech king Wenceslas IV, can be viewed by people in Prague's Klementinum today and on Saturday. The National Library has released them from its vaults to commemorate this year's 600th anniversary of Wenceslas's death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed the rare originals in display cases in the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free and it is open on both days from 10:00 to 18:00.
The exhibition of documents entitled Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the Royal Office and Library of Wenceslas IV was prepared by the library together with the National Archives. The National Archives looks at the written heritage from the reign of Wenceslas IV from the point of view of official documents and the National Library from the point of view of literary works, said its author Jan Vojtíšek.
"Visitors can look forward, for example, to the work on agriculture by Petr de Crescentiis, which is essentially a kind of encyclopedia of agriculture, or to the breviary, i.e. the prayer book of one of the Benedictine nuns of the monastery of St. George at Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15th century," he listed the reasons why people should, in his opinion, look at the exhibition.
The Epistles of Peter of Blois will also be on display, where the introductory miniature H (enrico) depicts the half-figure of the English king Henry II. The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who, in addition to the two volumes of the Bible of Wenceslas IV, also participated in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see the Latin collection of treatises by John Wycliffe from the period around 1411 to 1414.
Not a single book from the library of Wenceslas IV has been preserved on Czech territory. According to experts, this library belonged to the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in Central Europe at that time, because the young king longed to build a representative library that would match the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library disappeared soon after Wenceslas's death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed during the conquest of the castle by the Hussites. However, several codices were saved. Most of them are now owned by the Austrian National Library.
"We have a number of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a condition that allows them to be exhibited and made available to the public so-called live and not only in the form of the Manuscriptorium digital library," said the director of the National Library, Martin Kocanda.
On the day of Saturday's national holiday, an exhibition entitled What is hidden under the floor, which presents local archaeological discoveries, will also be open free of charge in Klementinum.
