Destroyed shops, fires in the streets, the memorial parade was accompanied by riots
Five years ago, 43 students from a high school in Ayotzinapa disappeared, and despite an extensive investigation, the case has not yet been solved. The students were allegedly detained by the police in the Mexican state of Guerrero. It is not clear exactly what happened next, but according to the investigation, the students apparently ended up in the hands of a local syndicate and were subsequently killed and burned, reports APTN.
A memorial procession was held in the Mexican capital on Thursday, with families expressing their frustration at the lack of answers and explanations for their children's disappearance.
The mostly peaceful march, however, was disrupted by smaller groups of vandals who destroyed everything in their path. The vandals destroyed shops and hotels, they did not shy away from destroying monuments, they set fires around the city and blew out windows.
Even before the march, President Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador said he would do everything possible to catch them and asked the public for any information that would lead to the clarification of the case.
More than 142 people were detained as part of the investigation, but not a single one of them was convicted. Many of them had to be released because their human rights were violated, the investigators allegedly tortured the suspects, APTN adds.
Putin calls Zelensky before start of ceasefire in Donbass, Kremlin criticizes planned elections
Russian President Vladimir Putin spoke on the phone with his Ukrainian counterpart Volodymyr Zelensky about the situation in Donbass, where a new ceasefire is due to come into effect at midnight.
According to a Kremlin statement, Putin, among other things, criticized the decision of the Ukrainian parliament to hold local elections; Kiev reported that Zelensky called for the release of detained Ukrainians.
A new ceasefire was agreed on Wednesday evening by negotiators from Ukraine and Russia with the support of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
The ceasefire is to begin after midnight on Monday night, is to be "complete and general" and is to pave the way for the fulfilment of other provisions of the peace agreements.
Putin told Zelensky in an interview that the decision of the Ukrainian parliament to hold local elections contradicts the Minsk peace agreement and threatens the prospects for settling the conflict in eastern Ukraine.
Last week, the Ukrainian parliament decided that the upcoming local elections would not be held in the territories controlled by pro-Russian rebels.
The Minsk agreement envisages that Kiev will regain control of the border of the Ukrainian territories occupied by separatists with Russia after granting broad autonomy to these regions and holding local elections there.
According to the Unian agency, Zelensky's office said that the two statesmen agreed on the benefits of the upcoming ceasefire in Donbass and on the need to carry out other measures to promote peace in the region, such as demining the areas of fighting or withdrawing part of the troops from the front.
Zelensky also called on Putin to release Ukrainians detained in the east of Ukraine, in the occupied Crimean peninsula and in Russia itself.
The Minsk agreement has helped to stop the fighting, but people continue to die on both sides of the front line in occasional gun battles and artillery attacks.
The conflict in Donbass has claimed more than 14,000 lives since the spring of 2014.
Ukraine and the West accuse Russia of providing military support to the separatists, which Moscow denies.
Zelensky has made ending the war in Donbass a priority, but so far there has been no major breakthrough in the negotiations.
And where are the spectators? Doha cannot be London
At the same time, however, it is a step back, because by making the pilgrimage to Doha, athletics has voluntarily and consciously renounced the thrilling atmosphere that prevailed at the sold-out stadium in London in 2017 and last year at the European Championships in Berlin.
Giant banners on the walls of Doha's skyscrapers invite people to the "biggest sporting event of 2019." However, concerns are growing about how dignified its backdrop will be.
"Tickets for the finish are sold out for all evenings," say the organisers.
But this is too little.
The upper gallery of the Khalifa Stadium, with a total capacity of 40 thousand spectators, is already covered with brightly colored sails, on which the flags of the 209 participating countries are also depicted. Athletics in Qatar has gone to a territory where, despite the annual Diamond League meeting, it has no roots.
It is therefore not surprising that last week only 50 thousand tickets were sold for the ten days of the championship, although their price started at 60 Qatari riyals, which is equivalent to less than 400 crowns.
The organizers have now set themselves the goal of filling at least half of the uncovered parts of the stands. Therefore, according to sources of the British newspaper Giuardian, they are allegedly (although the organizers themselves deny it) handing out free tickets to migrants who work here as workers, as well as to children. Sebastian Coe, head of the IAAF athletics association, can also comment positively: "This is how we can inspire the next generation."
Rich Qatar has won world championships in handball and cycling in the past, and after athletics comes football in 2022. The financial offers of the oil superpower will always be lucrative even for rich sports federations. This is the reality of today's sports world.
But even if we accept it and ignore the absence of fans in the stadium, we cannot avoid a purely sporting sigh that the leaders of the IAAF should have timed the experiment with the first outdoor world championship of athletes on the Arabian Peninsula better - and for another year. The extremely late deadline, forced by the climate, disrupts the entire scheme of the season in the pre-Olympic year and thus the preparation for the key Olympic season, which would normally begin for athletes in October.
Perhaps Qatar will at least make up for this with technological innovations, with the help of which it promises an ultra-modern and attractive championship. Isn't it 37 degrees right now? Even now, the area of the stadium is artificially air-conditioned to twenty-four. And advanced cameras, built directly into the blocks, are also supposed to give television viewers a detailed look at what is happening in the athletes in the hundredths of a second before the starter's shot and just after it.
