1. Definition of terms and rules of interpretation
1.1 In this Agreement, the following terms and phrases shall have the meanings set out below:
Acceptance procedure means the procedure by which the Customer accepts the Delivery.
Application means a computer program that complies with the specification and its scope is defined in Appendix 3 (Description of the Application and Documentation components).
A man-day means the work of one person for 8 (eight) working hours.
Documentation means a document that describes the Application, its functionalities, operation and outputs, and its scope is defined in Appendix No. 3 (Description of Application Components and Documentation).
Delivery means the Version, Upgrade or Patch that the Supplier delivers under this Agreement. Deliveries must follow each other and must be applied in a defined order, they must not be skipped. Each Delivery is numbered and contains the installation procedure and all relevant requirements within the meaning of the Delivery Cover Letter.
Project Charter means a document that formally governs the processes and communication between the Parties in the performance of the Contract. The Project Charter must be drawn up in accordance with the Project Management Methodology.
Incident means a difficulty that partially or completely prevents the use and operation of the Application, or means a problem with the functionality or data of the Application, and all this regardless of whether it is a defect of the Application or not. An incident can occur in the operating environment or in the acceptance environment.
Reporting an Incident means a request by the Customer to investigate and resolve the Incident.
Category A Incident means an Incident in the operational environment that prevents the use of the Application, or critical functions of the Application are inoperable and there is no possibility to circumvent such an Incident by using other functions of the Application, or has a direct negative impact on the end customer of the Authorized Entity. Some Category A Incidents are listed in Appendix No. 7 (Classification of Incidents).
Category B Incident means an Incident in the operational environment that restricts, but does not prevent the use of the Application, and it is possible to bypass it by using other functions of the Application. Some Category B Incidents are listed in Appendix No. 7 (Incident Classification).
Category C Incident means an Incident in the operational environment that is neither a Category A Incident nor a Category B Incident. Some Category C Incidents are listed in Appendix 7 (Incident Classification).
Incident of the TA category means an Incident in the acceptance environment that prevents the effective implementation of the Acceptance procedure, completely prevents the execution of a specific test scenario, or the critical functions of the Application are inoperative and there is no possibility to bypass such an Incident by using other functions of the Application. Some Incidents of the TA category are listed in Appendix No. 7 (Classification of Incidents).
Category TB Incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment that does not limit the effective implementation of the Acceptance Procedure, but prevents the execution or completion of a specific test scenario. Some Category TB Incidents are listed in Appendix No. 7 (Incident Classification).
A TC Incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment that is neither a TA Incident nor a TB Incident. Some TC Incidents are listed in Appendix 7 (Incident Classification).
The Project Management Methodology means the principles by which the provision of Services is organized. The Project Management Methodology establishes binding rules that, in accordance with the contractual arrangements between the Client and the Contractor, govern the management, coordination and control activities within the framework of the provision of Services. The Parties shall discuss, supplement, modify and approve the Project Management Methodology in the Project Charter. The Project Management Methodology is the content of Annex No. 6 (Project Management Methodology).
Civil Code means Act No. 89/2012 Coll., the Civil Code, as amended.
Remuneration means the remuneration of the Contractor for the provision of the Services. The method of calculating the Remuneration is set out in Appendix No. 2 (Remuneration).
Authorized entity means the Customer and the entity directly or indirectly controlled by any of the ultimate owners of the Customer.
Patch means an incremental change to the Application that resolves Incidents of category A or B in the operational environment or Incidents of category TA or TB or TC in the acceptance environment. The Patch is intended for a specific Upgrade or Patch. The Patch also includes the relevant Documentation. The Patch can only be deployed in connection with the Upgrade or Patch for which it is intended. The order of the Patches is defined by the Contractor and must be adhered to during deployment.
Working day means any day, except Saturday and Sunday and days on which a national holiday or other holiday falls according to the valid and effective legal regulations of the Czech Republic.
Working hour means 60 minutes at the time when the Contractor is obliged to provide the Service.
Accompanying document of the Delivery means a document that contains information about the essentials of the Delivery and information necessary for its application to the technological environment of the Customer.
Redmine means for the Application a dedicated part of the Redmine information system at helpdesk.jtfg.com
Service Level Agreement (hereinafter referred to as "SLA") means this Agreement, including all its annexes.
Service means each of the services listed in Schedule 1 (Services).
The Contract for Work means the contract concluded between the Contractor and the Client in accordance with Annex No. 13 (Contents of the Contract for Work). The subject of the Contract for Work is the execution of the work on the basis of the Change Documentation. The Contract for Work arises at the moment when the Client accepts the Contractor's offer in the form of the Change Documentation. The Contract for Work cannot be concluded orally. The content of the Contract for Work, unless otherwise agreed by the Parties in a particular case, is governed by Annex No. 13 (Contents of the Contract for Work).
Specification means a precise description of the Application, its features, functionalities and user interface, which constitutes Appendix No. 3 (Description of Application Components and Documentation).
Upgrade means an incremental change to the Application that enables the deployment of new functionality, a change to existing functionality or a change to the data in the Application compared to the current state of the Application. The upgrade consists of those elements of the Version in which the change occurred compared to the current state of the Application. The upgrade also contains a description of the method of testing for the new functionality that is in it. The current state of the Application is obtained by installing the last delivered Version and all subsequent Upgrades, and as part of the deployment of the Upgrade, all Patches that have been created since the previous Upgrade are also deployed, except for those that have not modified the functionality or control data of the Application. The relevant Documentation is also part of the Upgrade. Changes to the Application determined by the Customer and implemented on the basis of the Change Documentation and the resolution of Category C Incidents are included in the Upgrade.
Version means the complete state of the Application in a form that allows the complete and independent installation of the Application, including its settings, in such a way as to provide functionality in terms of the Specification and operational settings. The version contains (1) the version of the Application in the form of executable codes; and (2) the operational settings of the Application; and (3) the documentation of the Application.
Change control is the procedure by which a change is made to the Application and Documentation. The result of the Change Control is a change to the Application and Documentation that is in accordance with the change request.
