Annex No. 6 / Methodology of project management
1. Charter of the project
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and the method of communication between the parties in order to fulfill the subject of the Contract so that the execution of the work or the provision of services is in accordance with the Contract and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter makes available to the persons involved in the execution of the work or the provision of services those parts of the Contract that are necessary to fulfill its subject. The Project Charter determines the staffing of the organizational structure of the project, the method of communication, the control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal, where all documentation related to the execution of the work or the provision of services is archived. The Project Charter is prepared by the project managers and approved by the initial meeting of the Steering Committee.
2. Organization structure of the project
2.1 The organizational components of the Project are (1) the Project Steering Committee (hereinafter referred to as the "SCP") and (2) the Project Management Team (hereinafter referred to as the "PMT") and (3) the working teams. The SCP and the PMT are permanent organizational components of the Project. The working teams are temporary organizational components of the Project.
3. Steering committee
3.1 The powers of the SCP / Steering Committee of the project are in particular:
3.1.1 approves the Charter of the project; and
3.1.2 addresses escalated issues that have not been resolved at the PVP level; and
3.1.3 address issues with an impact on the scope of work performed or services provided; and
3.1.4 address issues related to the delivery schedule; and
3.1.5 address issues related to remuneration or the structure of remuneration for services provided or work performed; and
3.1.6 accepts individual deliveries, services, parts of the work or the work as a whole; and
3.2 Members of the SCP / On behalf of the Client, the members of the SCP are (1) the project sponsor for business and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the project manager. On behalf of the Contractor, the members of the SCP are (1) the management representative and (2) the project manager.
3.3 The SCP / SCP meets at least once a quarter. The exact days on which the SCP meets on a regular basis are determined by the project manager in the project charter. The SCP always meets when evaluating a significant milestone in the delivery schedule (e.g. the start or end of the acceptance procedure). The SCP always meets if a project manager invites the SCP to a meeting. The SCP meets at the headquarters of the Client.
3.4 The agenda of the SCP meeting / The agenda of the SCP meeting and the documents to be discussed will be delivered to the members of the SCP by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 3 working days before the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP will always discuss the project status report and draft minutes related to the acceptance of the delivery, services or work.
3.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / If a party considers it necessary, it has the right to invite experts or advisers to the SCP meeting, but it will inform the other party in advance and state the reasons why the presence of experts or advisers at the SCP meeting is useful.
3.6 Voting / After each item on the agenda has been discussed, the members of the SCP vote on the proposal submitted for the relevant item on the agenda. Each member of the SCP has one vote.
3.7 Decision of the SCP affecting the contractual conditions / If the decision of the SCP concerns the contractual conditions under which the work is performed or the services are provided, in particular if the decision of the SCP affects the remuneration for which the work is performed or the services are provided, the Client shall prepare an amendment to the contract in question without undue delay after the adoption of such a decision.
3.8 Minutes / The minutes of the SCP meeting shall be prepared by the project manager on behalf of the Client and delivered to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
4. Project management
4.1 Powers of the PVP / Project management of the project, in particular:
4.1.1 controls all the outputs of the individual stages of the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.2 evaluates and specifies the delivery schedule and the progress of work in the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.3 discusses amendments that do not affect the text of the Treaty; and
4.1.4 manages the cooperation between the Client and the Contractor; and
4.1.5 manage the risks and remedies associated with the performance of the work or the provision of the services; and
4.1.6 escalates to an SCP meeting.
4.2 Members of the PVP / On behalf of the Client the members of the PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief business analyst and (3) the application architect. On behalf of the Contractor the members of the PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief analyst and (3) the chief architect.
4.3 SCP / PVP meetings are held once a week, at the Customer's headquarters or by means of remote communication.
4.4 The agenda of the PVP meeting and documents / The agenda of the PVP meeting and documents to be discussed will be delivered to the PVP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor at least 1 working day before the PVP meeting. At its meeting, the PVP will always discuss:
4.4.1 implementation of the open tasks from the previous PVP; and
4.4.2 the progress of the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.3 the implementation and updating of the schedule of works; and
4.4.4 the problems identified and how they are being addressed; and
4.4.5 a plan for further action; and
4.4.6 risks associated with the performance of the work or the provision of the services; and
4.4.7 evaluation and other requirements for the cooperation of the Customer; and
4.4.8 the status and severity of unresolved defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 requirements for change; and
4.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / Both parties have the right to invite experts and advisers or members of project teams to the PVP negotiations if their presence is useful for the effective conduct of the negotiations.
4.6 Minutes / The minutes of the PVP meeting shall be prepared by the Project Manager on behalf of the Client and delivered to the Project Manager on behalf of the Contractor.
5. Work teams
5.1 Work teams / Work teams consist of employees of the Client or the Contractor and, where appropriate, employees of third parties. In particular, work teams (1) carry out specific parts of the work or services provided and (2) provide the know-how necessary for the execution of the work or the provision of services and (3) provide factual and professional basis for further decision-making.
5.2 Roles in work teams / Occupation of roles is always adapted to the current stage of execution of the work or provision of services. On the part of the Client, the members of the work team are:
5.2.1 Business analysts of the subject area / areas
5.2.2 Guarantor / key user of the subject area (s)
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the part of the Contractor, the members of the working team are:
5.2.4 Principal consultant/analyst - architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/Analyst
5.2.6 Technical infrastructure specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, trainer
5.2.9 Operation and installation specialist
6. A complete overview of the assignment of individual project roles and their communication matrix is determined by the Project Charter.
6.1 Communication management / Communication in the project is mainly managed by the project manager. Communication is always conducted in a factual manner with the aim of solving individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, managed, communication of project teams includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project meetings (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops, ...)
6.1.2 Acceptance and handover procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Record of change requests
6.1.5 Records of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - agenda and documents / The schedule and list of tasks from project meetings is always updated at the next meeting. The documents that will be the subject of the project meeting will be sent by the project manager to the participants of the meeting in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents are recorded and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes of project meetings / The Client's project manager shall prepare written minutes of each project meeting, which shall be delivered to the Contractor's project manager on the next working day after the project meeting.
6.4 Amendments and additions to the minutes of the project meeting / Amendments and additions to the minutes of the project meeting will be made by the participants within 2 working days from the date of delivery of the minutes. Negotiations on amendments and additions to the minutes are managed by the project manager. Amendments and additions to the minutes are not a place for discussion. After incorporating amendments and additions, the Client's project manager closes the minutes of the project meeting and stores it on the project portal. The deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting can be changed by the project managers by agreement. If any deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting expires without comments from the participants of the meeting, the minutes are considered approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and recording of risks / During the execution of the work or the provision of services, all persons involved identify and subsequently manage in a documented manner the risks that may affect the quality of the outputs or the deadlines for the execution of the work or the provision of services. Risks are recorded by the project manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussion of risks at the PVP meeting / Discussion and evaluation of risks is a mandatory item on the agenda of each PVP meeting. The PVP meeting sets out measures to eliminate or minimize risks.
7.3 Escalation / If there is a disagreement or if a risk is identified with a severity affecting the contractual arrangement or the schedule or the remuneration, such risk will be escalated by the PVP to the SCP meeting.
8. Quality management
8.1 The basic tool for managing the quality of project outputs is the acceptance procedure. The subject of quality verification is:
8.1.1 Checking the completeness of the subject of the work or the provision of services so that the purpose of the contract is fulfilled
8.1.2 Evaluation and settlement of comments, defects and incidents in order to fulfil the purpose of the contract
8.1.3 Checking that the documentation is up to date and complete
8.1.4 Control of compliance with the delivery schedule
8.1.5 Implementation of the approved changes
8.1.6 Results of other agreed activities according to the minutes of the meeting.
