Annex No. 7 / Classification of incidents
The items listed below are only inspirational. This appendix must be formulated precisely and exhaustively by the project manager.
Incidents from the operational environment
A category A incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
the user is unable to log into the Application
when the Application repeatedly crashes at the same step and the user cannot complete a critical process
when the system shows too long (double of the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
when it is not possible to print documentation or a report for a client
when incorrect data is displayed to the end customer
The critical functions/processes of the Application are:
opening or closing an account
start of daily closing
A category B incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
the work of the user is slowed down, but it does not have a serious impact on the workflow
when non-critical functionality is not available to the end customer.
A category C incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
if it is a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
Incidents from the acceptance environment
An incident in the TA category means an incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
it is not possible to create a client in the system
An incident in the TB category means an incident in the acceptance environment if, for example:
It is not possible to change any parameter of the client account
An incident of category TC means an incident in an acceptance environment if, for example:
if it is a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
