Overview of bank accounts for children on the Czech market
Children's accounts are provided by banks free of charge. However, it is necessary to consider the offer, because some other services for accounts are already charged. "The motivation of banks to offer accounts for children, whose basic management is usually free, is straightforward. Financial houses count on the fact that the waived fees will be returned to them one day. With a small migration of Czechs between banks, they are probably not wrong," says Kristýna Kuncová from dTest.
According to her, "small accounts" can do almost everything that accounts for adults can do. The child gets his or her own payment card, can enter payments, track movements on the account, and somewhere has his or her own electronic banking available. Banks will set up the account, but it is up to the parents to teach the children how to handle them and also to check their payments.
"Relatively flexibly, a parent can set weekly or monthly limits, turn on and off individual services, and so on. Above all, however, they can monitor what is happening on the account, whether by viewing it over the Internet or thanks to informational SMS. Beware, these may no longer be free," adds Kuncová, adding: "If a parent is considering an account for their child, they should consider their abilities and options."
The Museum in Semily returns to the Velvet Revolution with an exhibition
An imitation of a normalization room with a television showing footage of the brutal police intervention against students on 17 November 1989 in Prague. This is also in the new exhibition of the museum in Semily, which is dedicated to the Velvet Revolution. "The basis is to present what happened in Semily after the events on Národní třída," said the curator of the exhibition, Tomáš Chvátal.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the fact that the first demonstration was in Semily on 22 November, and then more people gradually gathered every day," he said. Among the most active at the beginning was a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the city and the immediate vicinity to sign Charter 77, and the Dědečková couple, who distributed the petition Several Sentences. According to Chvátal, the Civic Forum was also formed relatively quickly at that time. "One specific feature is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," said the curator.
Visitors should be drawn into the events in the city at that time by about 50 photographs, taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video from the general strike on 27 November 1989, shot by František Tomíček, has also been preserved and will be played on a loop for the entire duration of the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semily archive also lent a number of preserved banners from that time to the exhibition. "They said: Let's not get drunk with a roll, From trough to trough, We don't want violence," said Chvátal. Some changes in the city were very rapid at that time, for example, in December, people decided in a nationwide vote that the square would be Riegrovo and abolished the previous name Gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also captures the events before the November events. "In the first part, we present to witnesses and students what was before, such a late normalization. I think we managed to collect unique documents from Semily, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the former museum of the workers' movement," said Chvátal. One room is intended to evoke the feeling of what it might have looked like in the living room of an ordinary household at that time.
The last part of the exhibition is dedicated to what happened after the Velvet Revolution. It is focused on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Anyone who has experienced it will remember the posters With us to Europe or Václav Klaus is still there under the heading of the OF with the beautiful motto Everyone for their community," added the curator.
A pike in a pond or a relatively affluent open-air museum?
Babiš chose statistics for his optimistic view, such as good security (the Czech Republic is seventh in the world), a low unemployment rate, low national debt, or the fact that, according to a recent study, our country is twenty-fourth in quality of life out of 140 countries evaluated.
In a television interview on the occasion of the Summit of Architecture and Development, the developer Dušan Kunovský and the architect Josef Pleskot, however, cited other, far less "rosy" data. For example, the Czech Republic is in 154th place in the world in terms of the speed of construction procedures. It may happen that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant building heritage as it did in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only the existing legislation, but also the slow, inefficient bureaucracy. This is also documented by comparative studies, in which the Czech Republic lags significantly behind developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. Although it is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, people with an improving standard of living will also want to have a place to live, to travel in a modern and fast way, to have quality cultural stands, to live without an unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible for years to complete the inner and outer ring road or to build a high-speed railway or a metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, a concert hall or a national gallery. The reason for this is not only the absurd scramble for architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism that adheres to the motto "every bolder change is for the worse."
And when it seems that something more daring might succeed, it will almost certainly be thwarted by preservationists or other rather determined associations, or by politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding the "blob" of Jan Kaplický designed for the new building of the National Library, even President Václav Klaus wanted to tie himself to the excavators.
However, the list does not end with Prague. The Czech Republic is not able to complete its backbone motorway network, nor to start building high-speed train lines, so Germany finally decided to run its tracks for super-fast trains from Berlin to Vienna by "detouring" through Bavaria. In addition, repairs to existing infrastructure are sometimes drowned in slush. Getting quickly from Prague to Brno is now a puzzle.
Babiš came into politics with a promise to "fix things." However, when it comes to meaningful investments and speeding up cumbersome bureaucratic procedures, not much has happened so far. Although an amendment to the law on accelerating the construction of transport infrastructure has been in force since 2018, we will have to wait for more extensive positive effects, such as easier expropriation of land. And the new construction law, approved by the government, which is said to reduce the current average length of construction proceedings from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we are lucky, come into force in 2021. However, many people would probably not bet on it.
