Protests in Buhari: Pig's ears thrown by demonstrators at government building
Participants in a demonstration against Bulgarian Prime Minister Boyko Borisov and his cabinet have thrown pigs' ears at the government building.
It was the latest in a series of protests against the "mafia style of governance" that have been taking place in Sofia and other cities for almost three weeks.
Organizers are planning a nationwide blockade on Wednesday, the DPA news agency reported.
Today's protest, which took place for the 18th day in a row, had a weaker turnout than the previous one, according to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty.
About 300 people had gathered by 8 p.m., and some streets had to be closed to traffic.
Demonstrators in front of the government building staged a theatrical scene in which they symbolically locked up Prime Minister Borissov and Prosecutor General Ivan Geshev in a prison cell in connection with the arrest of two advisers to President Rumen Radev, who is a strong political opponent of the Prime Minister.
The resignation of both is one of the basic demands of the protesters.
They also demanded the cancellation of the announced health care reform and an end to corruption in construction on the Black Sea coast.
Protest organizer Nikolai Hadzhigenov said on public radio today that a "peak of escalation" is being prepared for Wednesday in the form of a "nationwide demonstration in Sofia and blockades throughout the country."
He reiterated the demand for the resignation of Borisov and his government, as well as the calling of early elections.
The regular ones should take place in March 2021.
Borisov has previously stated that he does not intend to resign.
He justified this, among other things, by the need to lead Bulgaria through the covid-19 pandemic and the resulting economic crisis.
On Friday, however, he replaced five members of his government team, although the concession did not appease the demonstrators.
Earlier this week, Borisov's government survived a vote of confidence in parliament.
The Attorney General has resumed the prosecution of a mother who manipulated her daughter against her father
The Supreme Public Prosecutor Pavel Zeman does not agree with the acquittal of the mother, who manipulated her daughter for a long time and disrupted her relationship with her father. She faced charges of abuse and endangering her upbringing. The Regional Court acquitted her of the charges, but Zeman does not agree with this. According to his appeal to the Supreme Court, such behaviour can be seen as a criminal offence.
The decision of the Supreme Court could have a wider impact on other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary from the point of view of regulating further application practice," Zeman's appeal states.
Last year, the District Court in Svitavy initially found the woman guilty of mistreating a person entrusted to her and endangering the upbringing of a child. She created a strong, almost symbiotic bond with her daughter, even in a situation where she was supposed to be entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a markedly negative relationship with the father. The situation affected the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalized because she threatened to harm herself if she was placed in the care of the father.
The Svitavy court sentenced the mother to two years in prison with a two-year suspended sentence. However, the Pardubice branch of the regional court acquitted the woman on appeal, saying it was not a criminal offence. The regional court repeated the same verdict even after the Supreme Court had already ordered it to decide again.
The Regional Court stated that situations where one of the parents manipulates the child against the other are by no means exceptional. They are dealt with in custody proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or youth welfare authorities. Only in exceptional cases is criminal law the solution.
According to the Supreme Public Prosecutor, however, the woman committed both abuse and endangerment of upbringing. "The accused acted quite purposefully when she aroused negative feelings in her daughter towards her father and purposefully reinforced these negative emotions. By acting in this way, she not only pursued the unlawful intention of limiting or excluding the father's contact with the minor, but she must necessarily have been aware that this would cause negative consequences in the psychosocial sphere of the minor," the appeal states.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to return the case once again to the regional court. It follows from the appeal that the child is now in the care of the father.
