Milan Jakubů: The army stole the funeral for itself! Says Andor Šándor
There are still uncertainties surrounding the funeral of Brigadier General Milan Jakubů. The media speculated this week that the army planned the last farewell to the Deputy Director of Military Intelligence, despite the wishes of the family, as bombastic as only soldiers can. There were also discrepancies regarding the date of the funeral. The spokesman for the Ministry of Defence, Jan Pejšek, denied this.
"It's nonsense! We have been in contact with the family from the beginning, the Friday date of the funeral has been agreed from the beginning, no one has changed it. The same applies to military honours. We will just deal with the possible participation of the media with regard to the family," Pejšek told Blesk on Wednesday. The funeral will finally take place on Friday and all military honours, including a flyover of fighter jets, will not be missing.
Even so, there is a tense atmosphere around the last farewell to the popular general. The organizers have decided that people who worked with the general in the past will not take part in the funeral ceremony!
One example is the former head of military intelligence, Andor Šándor (62), who met Milan Jakubů 17 years ago. Šándor remembers his former colleague as hard-working, intelligent and a "good guy."
In addition, in recent years he regularly met him at the celebrations of the anniversary of the founding of the Military Intelligence. That is why he would like to say goodbye to Milan Jakubů. "I personally would go to the funeral of Milan Jakubů," Šándor told Blesk. But he can't.
"I know of other people from the organization who would like to go, but they are out of luck, because the potentates are usurping the funeral for themselves. I think that it is not right to privatize the funeral in this way," said the security expert. He is also not amused by the allegedly considered closure of the ceremony to the public for reasons of secrecy of the military top brass.
"The leadership of the army is not classified and neither are the leaders of military intelligence, because they need to be promoted at Prague Castle, we can see them there. If the media information is true and the family really allowed themselves to be sidelined by the army, it is of course a matter for the family. Personally, I would never allow the army to override the family and its wishes," Šándor concluded.
