The launch of the new toll is not in jeopardy, reports Kremlík. However, a change of operator is in play.
On Friday, the Ministry of Transport began preparations for a new tender for the operation of a new toll system. This is a backup plan that the state would use in the event that the current toll contract is legally cancelled. In addition, the state is preparing other provisional solutions if the tender is not completed on time. This was announced on Facebook by the Minister of Transport Vladimír Kremlík (for ANO).
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Competition (UOHS) prohibited the performance of the toll contract between the state and the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium, with a one-year delay. The ministry will file an appeal against this.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not in jeopardy. Starting today, we are launching the preparation of a new transparent tender procedure, the subject of which will be the services of operating the new toll system, which is now being completed by the CzechToll and SkyToll consortium," said the minister.
In the tender, the state would be looking for the operator of the currently prepared toll, which will be launched from this December. It would not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case with the last tender, nor for the use of the old system, which is now operated by Kapsch.
However, according to Kremlík, the Ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not be able to prepare the new tender in time. "Based on the current experience with the course of the toll tender, I am deeply convinced that the OPC is wrong and that it is objectively impossible to prepare and implement such a complex tender procedure and hand over the operation of the toll system to a new operator within the 12-month period set by the OPC," he said.
In addition to the new tender procedure, the resort will also prepare a provisional solution that would solve the toll collection for a transitional period until the state finds a full-fledged form of solution.
The state will probably not yet make use of the offer made to it in recent days by the current toll administrator Kapsch. The Austrian company has offered the state the operation of the existing system in the event that the toll contract is cancelled.
At the same time, Kremlík reiterated that he believes that the backup plan will not be needed. Therefore, the ministry will file an appeal against the decision of the antitrust authority.
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Competition issued a decision prohibiting the performance of the toll contract. However, the ban will not come into force until one year after the authority's decision comes into force. This is not final and can be appealed to the chairman of the authority. The ministry and CzechToll are therefore continuing to prepare a new toll, which should be launched in December.
The CzechToll/SkyToll consortium won last year's tender for the new toll system and its operator. It succeeded in the toll tender with an offer of 10.75 billion crowns for ten years of operation. The current operator Kapsch protested against the course of the tender and the validity of the toll contract, which failed in the competition with an offer of over 13 billion crowns.
