There are up to 60 times fewer insects than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is radically shrinking. Another scientific study on this topic was published just this week, and the situation is even more serious than humanity has realized so far.
The study is based on field research in a tropical forest in Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, there are "ten to sixty times fewer insects" in the forest today. This is a decrease in the entire population, i.e. not in the number of species, and the research concerned not only insects, but all arthropods. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of other fauna that is dependent on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is also decreasing.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius over the past thirty years and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the team of authors, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously assumed.
"It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," said David Wagner, an entomologist at the University of Connecticut, who was quoted by the Post as an independent expert.
The extinction of insects also affects Europe. "In our country, the decline is also of an order of magnitude," points out Lukáš Čížek from the Institute of Entomology of the Academy of Sciences. According to him, in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account the changes in the landscape, which play a significant role in Europe. "In our country, it just takes a significantly longer time than in Puerto Rico," adds Čížek to explain why scientists were able to measure such a rapid decline in the forest compared to the 1970s.
