Ladies should learn from Saxana how not to underestimate themselves, that even on the threshold of their seventies they can take risks with their appearance. And it paid off for Petra, she looks no more than fifty.
Lucie Bílá's father was not a fan of her at all. You won't believe what she had to do for a living!
Who does not know that the national treasure Lucie Bílá (53) is originally a seamstress and her real name is Hana Zaňáková, probably does not live in the Czech Republic. But the singer herself has now revealed that she almost worked in a glass factory!
Lucie Bílá knew from a relatively early age that she wanted to be a singer. Her love for singing was born when, as a little girl, she performed in a cultural house in her native Otvovice, where the warbler still lives.
"And I remember exactly where my mother was sitting. At that time, a singer was born in me," she admitted to Impulsu radio.
Her father, however, was a little worried about his daughter's future and therefore advised her to follow the path of a craft that has a golden bottom.
"My dad always said: 'Craft girl, craft. Walk with your feet on the ground!' He even persuaded me to go to the local glassworks. The glassworks doesn't work anymore, but I do. I'm a trained seamstress and at home I make various rosaries and pendants from beads, which I then auction at auctions and use the money to buy wheelchairs," she added with a laugh.
The Děčín Zoo is delighted with the little macaque
"Our group currently has seven members. Its youngest member came into the world on 17 August, the female Buffy gave birth to him and he is her fifth cub, the father is the male Hitam. For the first few days after the birth, the female carried the cub tightly pressed to her body and for a long time she did not want to show the world whether she had given birth to a male or a female. However, at about three weeks of the cub's age, she gradually began to put it aside for a short while and the zookeepers have known for a few days that it is a male," said zoo spokeswoman Alena Houšková, adding that the Děčín Zoo has already successfully bred 12 cubs of this species.
Crested macaques are so-called endemic to the island of Sulawesi, which means that they do not live in the wild anywhere else in the world. A typical feature is black fur and a crest on the head, from which they get their name. Crested macaques live in rainforests, especially at lower altitudes.
Like most primates, it eats both plant and animal food. The diet is dominated by the fruits of forest trees, which complement the flowers and leaves. It solves the need for protein by eating small arthropods, larvae and, to a lesser extent, bird eggs and young.
"Apart from the natural enemies, which are pythons, everything else has been caused by humans. Locals hunt macaques as a popular prey with tasty meat and for fur. The burning and cutting down of the rainforest is also fatal for these animals," the spokeswoman added.
