The children told the police that they were taken to the school by their parents or relatives, saying that it was a religious school. "We have identified two children who come from Burkina Faso, but most of them were brought here by their parents from Nigerian states in the north," Sabo's spokesman said about the identity of the victims. Nigerian states in the north of the country are predominantly Muslim.
The Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal School purported to be a religious school dedicated to the study of the Koran.
Those freed have been taken to a stadium where they are being given aid and food, and some have already been reunited with relatives.
The fastest man on the planet missed the tests. I'm not taking anything, he defends himself
The traditionally high-profile battle for the fastest man on the planet will be a hunt for defending silver medalist Christian Coleman at the World Championships. The 23-year-old American is the world leader with a time of 9.81 seconds and has only lost once this year. However, his start at the top of the season was threatened due to a case of missed doping tests.
The United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case at the beginning of September without bringing charges due to formal reasons. Coleman did not take three doping tests last year and this year, but not within 12 months. His first offense was backdated by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) to April 1, 2018, i.e. to the beginning of the second quarter, but he did not miss the test itself until June 6. And since the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman did not commit an offense in the form of three failed tests within 12 months.
"I don't take drugs, I don't take anything legal. A lot of athletes take legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's about it," he said before the start of the World Championships.
His only defeat in six starts in the 100m this year came right at the start of the season at the Diamond League in Shanghai, where he was beaten by just six thousandths of a second by his compatriot Noah Lyles. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run the 200m at the World Championships.
On paper, the second fastest competitor is 22-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru with a performance of 9.86, but so far he has only been successful at American university competitions.
The title will be defended by the 37-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who shone with a time of 9.87 at Stanford in June. However, he only ran the last 100m in Zagreb in 10.29 because he slightly injured his hamstring.
South African Akani Simbine, three-time Rio Olympic medallist Andre de Grasse and European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favourites, while 2011 world champion Yohan Blake is the fastest Jamaican with a time of 9.96.
The men's 100m will begin on Friday with the preliminary round and heats. The semi-finals and final are scheduled for Saturday. The medals will be awarded at 21:15 CEST.
EU countries have coronavirus standards for aviation
European Union countries have agreed on common hygiene standards for air travel to help limit the spread of the new coronavirus.
This was announced by the German Transport Minister Andreas Scheuer.
Among the agreed standards is keeping a distance or wearing masks on the plane and at the airport, but middle seats on planes will not have to remain unoccupied.
This was reported by Reuters.
"I am glad that my colleagues have accepted the German proposal for Europe and that we have been able to agree on these uniform standards," said Scheuer at the European Aviation Conference.
The German transport ministry then added that the agreement had been concluded by officials and that it still had to be formally approved by ministers.
The agreed measures include the requirement to cover the mouth and nose for passengers from the age of six, to observe the recommended distance during security checks and check-in at the airport.
Fresh air must also be guaranteed on board and all information must be available in several languages.
Airlines will also be able to fill middle seats.
The common rules agreed by officials meet at least some of the airlines' demands.
The different standards were causing confusion.
