Soldiers rehearse, pull down the curtains. China prepares celebrations at the site of the massacre
The military rehearsed the parade on recent weekends, with shops in central Beijing forced to close and residents near the square ordered to close their curtains as military vehicles rolled down empty streets toward the square and fighter jets circled the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters they were proud that their country would be showing off its military might, but one woman said it was hard to deny that the celebrations would make other countries uneasy.
She appeared to be referring to Taiwan, which China claims and where elections are coming up, but there may also be concern in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, where thousands of people have repeatedly demonstrated against the Chinese-appointed leader.
Celebrations are also being prepared outside of Beijing. The southern Chinese port of Xiamen already presented a special light show on Thursday night. Xiamen is located opposite the island of Taiwan and is one of the ten most innovative Chinese cities.
Ahead of the anniversary, the list of banned items is growing and already includes drones, balloons, kites, alcohol, walkie-talkies and devices that use radio waves, The Guardian reported, adding that China's popular social network Weibo is deleting "harmful political information."
"It's another milestone, another opportunity to show that the Chinese Communist Party remains (at the helm) despite all the predictions," said China historian Maura Cunningham. "It's a moment when the party can demonstrate order, control and power," she added.
The People's Republic of China was formed in 1949 when the Communists, led by Mao Zedong, won a battle with Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists, who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of the 1960s, China went through a disastrous communist experiment in the form of the so-called Cultural Revolution. In June 1989, the regime massacred thousands of pro-democracy demonstrators, both students and workers, with tanks in Tiananmen Square.
Since the late 1970s, China has increasingly taken on elements of a capitalist economy; critics say it is now a mixture of the worst of both communism (one-party monopoly and persecution of the opposition) and (Dickensian) capitalism (exploitation of workers).
