Trump is considering canceling the registration of Chinese stocks in the US
The administration of U.S. President Donald Trump is considering revoking the permission of Chinese companies to trade on stock markets in the United States, an informed source told Reuters today. Such a move would be a radical escalation of trade tensions between the U.S. and China. Shares of the companies concerned on the New York Stock Exchange immediately headed down after the report, dragging the entire market down with them.
The pullback would be part of a broader effort to limit U.S. investment in China, the source added, confirming a Bloomberg report that had sent shockwaves through financial markets earlier in the day, with shares of Chinese firms Alibaba Group Holding, JD.com, Pinduoduo, Baidu, Vipshop Holdings, Baozun and IQIYI falling between 2 percent and 4 percent.
According to government data from February, 156 Chinese companies are traded on the US stock exchanges Nasdaq and NYSE, including at least 11 state-owned enterprises.
Bloomberg pointed out that a precise mechanism has not yet been worked out to ensure the withdrawal of shares of Chinese companies from US stock exchanges. A possible plan would have to be approved by Trump, who, however, gave the green light to negotiations on this matter.
China and the United States have been waging a trade war for more than a year, imposing tariffs on each other. The dispute between the two countries has a negative impact on the world economy and raises fears of a global economic recession. Washington is trying to use tariffs to force Beijing to change its trade practices and reduce China's trade surplus with the United States.
According to CNBC, trade negotiations between the U.S. and China are expected to resume on October 10, with the aim of ending the trade war.
Former French President Chirac to be buried on Monday, public memorial on Sunday
The funeral of former French President Jacques Chirac, who died on Thursday at the age of 86, will take place on Monday evening at the Montparnasse cemetery in Paris, French media report, citing the Chirac family. The ceremony will be private.
The public will be able to say goodbye to the former head of state on Sunday afternoon at a memorial service at the Invalides in Paris, where a coffin with Chirac's remains will be displayed, the Elysée Palace announced.
According to the AFP news agency, crowds of people have been flocking to the presidential residence since Thursday evening to sign the book of condolences. This will be possible until Sunday. President Emmanuel Macron has declared a national day of mourning on Monday.
From the world and from France, meanwhile, come more reactions to the death of the former mayor of Paris and president from 1995 to 2007, whom Prime Minister Édouard Philippe today described as "French in the true sense of the word."
Chirac was remembered, for example, by the Japanese, since the politician was known for his love of their country and the sport of sumo. The news of the death of the former French president appeared on the front pages of all Japanese newspapers, including sports ones, the French press notes.
The Museum of Tribal Art on the Quai Branly in Paris, which Chirac founded, will not charge admission for ten days in honour of the former head of state.
A temperature record was set in the Arctic Svalbard, where it was almost 22 degrees
"A 41-year-old record has been broken in Longyearbyen," the Norwegian Meteorological Institute said on Twitter.
In the early evening, the temperature there rose to 21.7 degrees Celsius, beating the record set in 1979 by 0.4 degrees, he added.
Longyearbyen, with a population of around 2,000, is the largest town in Svalbard and is located about 1,300 kilometres from the North Pole.
Svalbard is warming faster than almost any other place on Earth.
This highlights the dangers posed by the warming of other parts of the Arctic - from Alaska to Siberia, according to a report last year by the Norwegian Centre for Climate Studies.
According to him, the average temperature in Svalbard has risen by three to five degrees since the 1970s.
It could rise by as much as ten degrees by 2100 if greenhouse gas emissions into the atmosphere are not reduced.
The rise in temperature may result in the melting of the permafrost in Svalbard, which will threaten the stability of many buildings, roads or airports and may also cause more avalanches and landslides.
The warming of the climate also threatens Arctic fauna, such as polar bears and seals, which depend on the ice cover of the ocean.
