The car tuner brought the voice of the digital soul
Everything you know about obesity is wrong, declares the headline of a long text written for the Huffington Post by Michael Hobbes and photographed by Finlay Mackay. In a provocative explanation, it says that the medical community has ignored the facts about obesity for decades and waged a ruthless (and also unnecessary) war against overweight people, which has not only affected public opinion, but also destroyed a lot of lives. But now it is time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes mentions right at the beginning is the fact that there is often a very long and tedious path from knowledge and knowledge of the facts to putting it into practice. He mentions the case of scurvy, when some captains in the seventeenth century distributed lemons, limes and oranges to their crew in the belief that they would prevent the disease. However, the British Navy withdrew from this practice due to fears of increased costs. The clear influence of the fruit in the prevention and treatment of the disease was then proven in the middle of the 18th century, but it took another fifty years for the Navy to take it into account. Seat belts also existed long before the invention of the car, but they became mandatory only in the 1960s, as well as the first confirmed death in connection with asbestos dates back to 1906, but its first ban came in 1973.
In American society today, nearly 80 percent of the adult population and about one-third of children meet the definition of being overweight or obese. More Americans now live with obesity than with breast cancer, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and HIV combined.
Obesity is seen as a highly personal failure of the individual, which is said to burden health care and reduce GDP. The fear of fatness is so great in the population that Americans now spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and films. But the truth is that diets do not work. As early as 1959, research showed that 95 to 98% of attempts to lose weight end in failure, and two-thirds of people on a diet subsequently gain more weight than they lost.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes goes on to describe the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people. Here, the personal meets the systemic, where, for example, in faculties teaching future doctors, only 19 hours of the entire course are devoted to the issue of nutrition. This at a time when 60% of the calories that Americans consume come from ultra-processed food.
The way obesity is stigmatised is illustrated by reports from surgeries, where overweight people tend to have shorter check-ups, are treated with less empathy by doctors and are seen as more problematic patients.
But being overweight is far from just an American problem, as Hobbes writes. Since 1980, the rate of obesity has doubled in 73 countries and increased in 113, and no country has been able to slow or stop the increase. Absolutely none.
