Duplantis is miles ahead, it's a kick in the ass, laments the Swede's challenger
It is the 22-year-old American pole vaulter who has the ambition and potential to be among the most serious competitors of the new ruler.
He already knows what it's like to beat Duplantis, who is two years younger; he beat him at the NCAA meeting last year.
"We had a battle the year before, when he won and I was second, and then we switched.
In both cases, it was a very good fight," describes Nilsen, who secured the victory with a performance of 5.95 meters.
But Duplantis has shot up since then and is currently alone at the top of the pole vaulting world.
At just 20 years of age, he became a world record holder, breaking the bar of 6.17 metres in Torun on 8 February this year, and adding another centimetre in Glasgow a week later.
"He was already jumping six meters at the age of 18 when he finished high school," recalls his peer Nilsen for the World Athletics website.
"It was clear that once he matured from a boy into a man, all his potential and talent would be multiplied tenfold.
Twenty years old is a pretty good age to jump a world record," he said.
Although Nilsen's list of achievements is considerably thinner than that boasted by Duplantis, the American has similar goals.
So far, he has hinted at his potential at NCAA competitions, which he has regularly won. In February of this year, he improved his indoor personal best to 5.93 m at one of them. Last August, he won a gold medal at the Pan American Games in Lima, and in 2017 he made it to the American team for the World Championships, where he finished 13th.
The next milestone for him is to taste the Diamond League for the first time.
"Definitely my priority is to get on the professional circuit and race as much as I can in the Diamond League because that's where you can make a name for yourself," he realises.
"If you can succeed at this level, there is no doubt that you can do the same at events like the Olympic Games, the World Championships or the Pan American Games."
Due to the pandemic, however, these top holidays are being postponed, which gives Nilsen and the other pole vaulters time to improve.
But will it be enough to catch Duplantis, who can easily turn the race below the five rings into a mere battle for silver?
"Everyone is trying to catch up with him, but I don't think it will be possible in the near future," Nilsen said.
"This kid has been jumping for 16 years and he's miles ahead of everyone else in training."
And before Tokyo 2021 begins, he will want to increase it even more.
For their study, the researchers are looking for toddlers with a congenital defect known as ankle valgus.
Valgosity of the ankles is a congenital defect that affects five to ten percent of children. It is normally treated with intensive exercise. Scientists are trying to help these children even more, so they have developed special shoes that should significantly speed up the treatment.
"We have two prototypes of shoes that will be worn by healthy children and children with a diagnosis in order to map the effect in both groups. Participation in the research will not have any risks for the children and the measurement will be completely painless," explains Marta Gimunová, head of research from the Faculty of Sports Studies at MU.
Parents of both groups of children can register for the study via the website, where the registration form and all information is available.
The researchers are looking for fifty children with a diagnosis and fifty healthy children. Of each group, half will always wear medical shoes and half will not.
"The moment when parents should register their child is when they take their first independent steps, typically letting go of furniture, for example, which they hold on to when trying to walk. Participation in the research involves three measurements over the course of seven months from the child's first steps, each of which takes about 20 minutes, and for half of the participants it also includes wearing the tested shoes," Gimunová points out.
The opening of Pumpkin World has delayed the ripening of pumpkins
Nová Ves u Leština (Havlíčkobrodsko) - A farm in Nová Ves u Leština in the Havlíčkobrodsko region opened the Pumpkin World today for more than a month. Decorations made up of thousands of freshly harvested pumpkins are dominated by massive orange pyramids in the garden. The autumn event, which is becoming a tradition, starts a week later this year because the pumpkins on the surrounding seven hectares of the Pipkova family's fields have matured longer. There are still a lot of them in the field, Jaroslava Pipková told ČTK today.
The Pipkas grow many types of pumpkins, but the weather has not been good for the last two years. This year's harvest was delayed and some types did not work out. "As usual, we have enough orange pumpkins for Halloween, but some types for connoisseurs did not work out," said Pipková. Nevertheless, there are more types to choose from on the farm, from the already mentioned large pumpkins suitable for carving and chiseling decorations to pumpkins for cooking hokaido or elongated "spaghetti" to ornamental gourds of various colors and shapes.
Growing pumpkins is laborious. Farmers manually hoe the plants and harvest their fruits, and cut the pumpkins from the stem with scissors. Pipka's Pumpkin World has been open regularly since 2010, and past years have attracted thousands of people. The pumpkin decorations are complemented by attractions made of straw or a maze made of logs. Visitors will also see animals kept on the farm. It will be open daily until November 3.
Details of the event are on the farm's website, where growers also offer some recipes for pumpkin dishes, such as pumpkin muffins or juice. Visitors themselves tell them about other ways to prepare pumpkin in the kitchen. "A lot of cooks have tried their recipes, and we will be inspired," said Pipková. She noted that some housewives also pickle pumpkins like cucumbers.
