Unkempt man wants 45 million from the state
According to the spokesman of the office, Vladimír Řepka, the Ministry of Justice has so far received six requests in this regard and is now analysing them. The young man was in prison for two years for assaulting a woman, but the judiciary finally acquitted him.
Neither the Supreme Public Prosecutor Pavel Zeman nor the Minister of Justice Marie Benešová filed an appeal in the case.
The attempted murder of a hairdresser in Hořice happened in February 2013. The Hradec Králové Public Prosecutor's Office charged the then 20-year-old grammar school student Nečesaný. The prosecution claimed that he hit the woman several times in the head with a log and then took over ten thousand crowns from her. The seriously injured woman was found by her son, and her life was saved by doctors at the Hradec Králové hospital.
"I am innocent and I swear to it. I am sincerely sorry for what happened to the victim, but I am not the perpetrator," the young man said earlier in court, who did not deny that he was in the hairdresser's on the fateful day. He said he wanted to get a haircut. But he left after the woman told him that she was already closing. He then turned himself in to the police as a witness.
At first, the hairdresser did not recognize him as the aggressor during the interrogation, but later she identified Nečesaný as the attacker. According to court experts, she suffered from memory loss after the attack.
The Hradec Králové Regional Court handed down five verdicts in the case. First, it found Nečesaný guilty twice and sentenced him to 16 years in prison, while the High Court of Appeal reduced his sentence to 13 years. Nečesaný was sent to prison twice, but each time he was released after the intervention of the Supreme Court. After the ordered replacement of the court panel, there were repeated acquittals, the last of which was confirmed by the High Court in March this year.
At the same time, however, the Chairman of the Board of Appeal, Jiří Lněnička, stated in the reasoning of his conclusions that this decision was wrong, but due to the procedural situation, he did not have a better option. He said that he rejected the appeal of the public prosecutor against the acquittal verdict, even though her appeal objections were justified.
"The problem of this case is not that there is a lack of evidence, but their evaluation. We believe that a sufficient amount of evidence was collected in the pre-trial proceedings, which would be more than sufficient in another criminal case for the recognition of guilt," said Lněnička.
However, the Hradec Králové Court, as well as the Supreme Court, looked at the case differently and their opinion would probably not change if the acquittal were to be overturned.
